Thus Zeus brought Hector and the Trojans to the ships.\uc0\u8232 Then he left the soldiers there to carry on their strife,\u8232 their wretched endless war. He turned his shining gaze\u8232 away from them, looking far off into the distance,\u8232 at the land of Thracian horsemen, Mysians,\u8232 men who fight hand to hand, proud Hippemolgi,\u8232 who drink mare\'92s milk, to the most righteous men of all,\u8232 the Abii. Zeus no longer turned his radiant eyes\u8232 toward Troy, for in his heart he did not believe\u8232 a single one of the immortal gods would move\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a010\u8232 to give assistance to the Trojans or Danaans.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\
But mighty Earthshaker Poseidon was keeping watch.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[10]\uc0\u8232 High on the tallest crest of wooded Samothrace\u8232 he sat looking down upon the war going on.\u8232 From that point, Mount Ida was clearly visible,\u8232 Priam\'92s city, too, and the Achaean ships.\u8232 He\'92d come up from the sea and seated himself there,\u8232 pitying Achaeans, as Trojans beat them back,\u8232 and nursing a powerful anger against Zeus.\u8232 Poseidon came down quickly from that rocky peak,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a020\u8232 moving swiftly on his feet. Mountain peaks and woods\u8232 trembled under Poseidon\'92s immortal stride.\u8232 He took three paces\'97with the fourth he reached his goal,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[20]\u8232 Aegae, where his famous palace had been built\u8232 of eternal gold and marble deep within the sea.\u8232 Going inside, he harnessed to his chariot\u8232 swift bronze-hooved horses with flowing golden manes.\u8232 Dressed in gold, he took his well-made golden whip,\u8232 climbed in the chariot, then set off across the waves.\u8232 From the depths, sea creatures played around him everywhere,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a030\u8232 acknowledging their king. The joyful ocean parted.\u8232 He sped on quickly, keeping the bronze axle dry.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[30]\u8232 The prancing horses carried him to the Achaean ships.\
Half-way between Tenedos and rocky Imbros,\uc0\u8232 a wide cavern sits deep within the sea. In that spot,\u8232 Earthshaker Poseidon reined in his horses,\u8232 freed them from the chariot, and threw down ambrosia,\u8232 food for them to eat. Around their feet he placed\u8232 golden hobbles which they could not slip or break,\u8232 so they\'92d remain secure there till their lord\'92s return.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a040\u8232 Then Poseidon moved on to the Achaean camp.\
At that point, Trojans, like some fire or windstorm,\uc0\u8232 marched behind Hector, son of Priam, in a mass,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[40]\u8232 shouting and screaming with excitement, hoping\u8232 to seize Achaean ships and kill the best men there.\u8232 But Poseidon, who encircles and shakes the earth,\u8232 roused the Argives, once he\'92d moved up from the sea.\u8232 Taking on the shape and tireless voice of Calchas,\u8232 he first spoke to the Ajaxes, both keen to fight.\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93You Ajaxes, you must save Achaean troops.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a050\uc0\u8232 Think of your fighting power, not cold flight.\u8232 In other places, I don\'92t fear the Trojans,\u8232 whose powerful arms have brought hordes of them\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[50]\u8232 across our wall. For well-armed Achaeans\u8232 will check them all. But I fear them here,\u8232 where we may experience disaster,\u8232 because of Hector, who leads their charge.\u8232 He\'92s like a man possessed, a blazing fire,\u8232 as if he were a son of mighty Zeus.\u8232 But perhaps some god will inspire the hearts\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a060\u8232 in both your chests, so you two can stand firm.\u8232 You could get other men to do the same.\u8232 Hector may be keen, but you could push him\u8232 back from our swift ships, even if Zeus himself\u8232 is driving him ahead.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Poseidon finished speaking.\uc0\u8232 Then, the shaker and encircler of the earth\u8232 touched both men with his staff, infusing them\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[60]\u8232 with power, strengthening their legs and upper arms.\u8232 Then Poseidon left. Just as a swift-winged hawk\u8232 takes off while hovering above some high sheer rock,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a070\u8232 swooping down over the plain to hunt another bird\'97\u8232 that how Earthshaker Poseidon went off then.\u8232 Swift Ajax, son of O\'efleus, was the first\u8232 to recognize the god. At once he spoke to Ajax,\u8232 son of Telamon:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Ajax, one of the gods\uc0\u8232 dwelling on Olympus, in a prophet\'92s shape,\u8232 tells us both to fight on by the ships.\u8232 For that man was no prophet Calchas,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[70]\u8232 who reads our omens. It was easy for me,\u8232 as he went away, to see that from the back\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a080\u8232 by the markings on his feet and legs.\u8232 Besides, it\'92s easy to recognize the gods.\u8232 So now the spirit here in my own chest\u8232 is even keener than before to fight.\u8232 My upper arms have lots of energy.\u8232 I feel it also in my lower limbs.\'94\
Telamonian Ajax then answered O\'eflean Ajax:\
\'a0\'93I\'92m ready to wrap my conquering hands\uc0\u8232 around my spear. My fighting power grows.\u8232 My feet can now move fast. So I\'92m eager\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a090\u8232 to meet Hector, son of Priam, one on one\'97\u8232 the man whose fury so desires this fight.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[80]\
As the two Ajaxes talked like this to one another,\uc0\u8232 relishing the warlike spirit the god had put\u8232 into their hearts, the Encircler of the Earth\u8232 was encouraging Achaeans at the rear,\u8232 those whose spirits were recovering by the swift ships,\u8232 their limbs exhausted from their anguishing ordeals,\u8232 their hearts weighed down with sorrow at the sight\u8232 of Trojan soldiers coming over their great wall.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0100\u8232 When they saw that, their eyes shed tears\'97they thought\u8232 they\'92d not escape destruction. Earthshaker Poseidon\u8232 moved round with ease, bringing strength into the ranks.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[90]\u8232 He moved first to encourage Teucer and Le\'eftus,\u8232 then brave Peneleous, Thoas, De\'efpyrus,\u8232 then Meriones and Antilochus, both skilled\u8232 in war shouts. He spoke to them\'97his words had wings:\
\'93Shame on you Argives, nothing but young boys!\uc0\u8232 I\'92m counting on your strength to save our ships.\u8232 If you\'92re holding back in this grim fight,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0110\u8232 then now\'92s the day the Trojans overcome us.\u8232 Alas! What my eyes witness here astounds me,\u8232 a dreadful thing I never thought would happen\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[100]\u8232 Trojans moving up to our own ships,\u8232 men who previously were shy, like deer,\u8232 which in the woods are prey to jackals,\u8232 wolves, and leopards, as they wander round,\u8232 alone and frightened, with no will to fight.\u8232 Before now, Trojans never wished to stand\u8232 confronting the fierce fighting power\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0120\u8232 of Achaean arms, not even for a moment.\u8232 But now, far from their city, they fight here,\u8232 right by our hollow ships. And the reason\'92s this\'97\u8232 our leadership\'92s been bad, our army slack.\u8232 For those who quarrel with our general\u8232 won\'92t protect our fast-moving ships from harm,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[110]\u8232 and so are being cut down among them there.\u8232 But even if wide-ruling Agamemnon,\u8232 heroic son of Atreus, is to blame,\u8232 if he really is the reason for all this,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0130\u8232 because he treated swift Achilles badly,\u8232 in this battle we must hold back nothing.\u8232 Let\'92s fix all this\'97and quickly. In their hearts\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 fine men can change. It\'92s bad if you restrain\u8232 your fighting spirit any longer,\u8232 especially you, the best of all our troops.\u8232 Myself, I wouldn\'92t argue with a man\u8232 not keen to fight because he is a coward.\u8232 But in you my heart is disappointed.\u8232 Friends, by this hanging back you\'92ll help to make\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0140\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[120]\u8232 an even worse disaster. Let each of you\u8232 feel shame and indignation in his heart.\u8232 A great battle has just started. Hector,\u8232 skilled at war cries, is fighting by our ships.\u8232 His force has smashed our gates, our long bolts, too.\'94\
By rousing men this way, Earthshaker Poseidon\uc0\u8232 pushed Achaeans into action. Round both Ajaxes\u8232 soldiers made a stand and strongly held their ground.\u8232 If Ares had come there, he would have approved of them,\u8232 as would Athena, who inspires men in war.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0150\u8232 Those known for their great bravery did not back off.\u8232 They fought lord Hector and the Trojans spear for spear,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[130]\u8232 shield with layered shield, in close-packed formation,\u8232 shields linked together and helmet touching helmet,\u8232 troops shoulder to shoulder. As men moved their heads,\u8232 horsehair crests on shining helmet ridges touched\'97\u8232 that\'92s how densely packed they stood in that formation.\u8232 Their strong hands held the spears out so they overlapped.\u8232 Their minds were firm and fully ready for the fight.\
The Trojans came on in a mass, led by Hector,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0160\uc0\u8232 always charging forward, like a rolling boulder,\u8232 which some river in a winter flood dislodges\u8232 from a cliff beside its banks, its great flood eroding\u8232 what supports that lethal stone. In its fall, it bounces\'97\u8232 woods crash underneath it, as it accelerates\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[140]\u8232 in a straight line, unimpeded\'97then it hits the plain,\u8232 where, for all its impetus, its motion stops.\u8232 That\'92s how Hector threatened then to smash his way\u8232 with ease down to the sea, to Achaea\'92s huts and ships.\u8232 But when he ran into the tight-packed lines of men,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0170\u8232 he came close but was held in check. Achaea\'92s sons\u8232 faced up to him with swords, with double-bladed spears,\u8232 and pushed him back. Shaken, Hector had to give ground.\u8232 He let out a piercing shout, calling to his Trojans:\
\'93Trojans, Lycians, you Dardan spearmen,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[150]\uc0\u8232 hold your place. Achaeans won\'92t keep me back,\u8232 not for long. Even though they\'92ve set themselves\u8232 in a defensive wall, I think they will retreat\u8232 before my spear, if the greatest of the gods,\u8232 Hera\'92s loud-thundering mate, inspires me.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0180\
Saying this, Hector gave heart and spirit to each man.\uc0\u8232 De\'efphobus, son of Priam, moved out before them,\u8232 full of ambitious hopes. Holding his round shield\u8232 in front of him, he stepped lightly forward,\u8232 under cover of that shield. Then Meriones\u8232 after taking aim, threw his shining spear at him.\u8232 He didn\'92t miss. He struck that round leather shield.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[160]\u8232 But the spear did not break through. Before it could,\u8232 it snapped off at the socket. Then De\'efphobus,\u8232 his heart afraid of warlike Meriones\'92 spear,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0190\u8232 held his leather shield at arm\'92s length away from him.\u8232 But Meriones had withdrawn into the group\u8232 of his companions, upset at his double loss\'97\u8232 the victory and the spear which he\'92d just shattered.\u8232 He set off for the Achaean huts and ships,\u8232 to fetch another spear he\'92d left inside his hut.\
The others kept on fighting. The din was constant.\uc0\u8232 The first to kill a man was Teucer, son of Telamon.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[170]\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 He slew Imbrius, a spearman, son of Mentor,\u8232 who owned many horses. He\'92d lived in Pedaeum\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0200\u8232 before Achaea\'92s sons arrived. He married\u8232 one of Priam\'92s bastard daughters, Medesicaste.\u8232 When the curved ships of the Danaans came to Troy,\u8232 he went back. The people there thought much of him.\u8232 He lived with Priam, who honoured him as well,\u8232 as if he were his child. But the son of Telamon\u8232 with a long spear thrust hit Imbrius below the ear.\u8232 Teucer pulled the weapon back. Imbrius collapsed.\u8232 Just as an ash tree growing on a mountain top,\u8232 visible from every side, is chopped down by bronze,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0210\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[180]\u8232 its foliage crashing to the ground\'97that\'92s how he fell.\u8232 His armour, finely decorated bronze, rang out,\u8232 reverberating round him. Teucer then jumped out,\u8232 eager to strip away his armour, but as he charged,\u8232 Hector threw a shining spear at him. Teucer,\u8232 seeing it coming, safely dodged the bronze spear point.\u8232 But Hector\'92s spear hit Amphimachus, son of Cteatus,\u8232 Actor\'92s son, in the chest, as he was coming up,\u8232 about to join the battle. He fell with a crash,\u8232 his armour echoing around him. Hector ran up,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0220\u8232 eager to tug away the helmet tightly bound\u8232 around the temples of brave Amphimachus.\u8232 But with his bright spear Ajax lunged at Hector,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[190]\u8232 as he came forward. He didn\'92t touch his flesh,\u8232 for Hector was encased in terrifying bronze.\u8232 But Ajax struck the central boss on Hector\'92s shield,\u8232 and his great power pushed him back. Hector withdrew\u8232 and left the corpses, so Achaeans dragged them off.\u8232 Amphimachus was carried back to the Achaean troops\u8232 by Stichius and by noble Menestheus,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0230\u8232 who led Athenian troops. The two Ajaxes,\u8232 still full of battle rage, hauled Imbrius away.\u8232 As two lions snatch a goat from sharp-toothed hounds,\u8232 then take it in their jaws off through thick underbrush,\u8232 holding it well off the ground, that\'92s how both Ajaxes\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[200]\u8232 held Imbrius up. They stripped off his armour.\u8232 In his anger at the killing of Amphimachus,\u8232 O\'eflean Ajax hacked through the tender neck,\u8232 then, with a swing of his body, threw away the head,\u8232 like some ball, into the crowd. It fell into the dust,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0240\u8232 right at Hector\'92s feet.\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0At that point, Poseidon,\uc0\u8232 angry that his grandson Amphimachus had died\u8232 in that harsh fight, went through Achaea\'92s huts and ships,\u8232 rousing Achaeans, planning trouble for the Trojans.\u8232 He met the famous spearman Idomeneus\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[210]\u8232 coming from a comrade who\'92d just left the fight.\u8232 A sharp bronze blow had struck him in the knee.\u8232 His companions brought him in. Idomeneus,\u8232 having issued his instructions to the healers,\u8232 was going to his hut, still eager to fight on.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0250\u8232 The mighty Earthshaker spoke to him, making his voice\u8232 sound like Thoas, son of Andraemon, who ruled\u8232 Aetolians all through Pleuron and steep Calydon,\u8232 honoured by his people like a god:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Idomeneus,\uc0\u8232 Cretan counsellor, what\'92s happened to those threats\u8232 Achaea\'92s sons once made against the Trojans?\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[220]\
