\'93You arrogant Trojans, who can\'92t get enough\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[620]\uc0\u8232 of war\'92s destructive noise, this is the way\u8232 you\'92ll go back from these ships of the Danaans,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0730\u8232 who ride fast horses. You\'92re not reluctant,\u8232 where insults and dishonour are concerned,\u8232 to go after me, you worthless mongrel dogs,\u8232 without fearing in your hearts harsh anger\u8232 from thundering Zeus, god of hospitality,\u8232 who some day will destroy your lofty town.\u8232 For you carried off the wife I married,\u8232 lots of my property, and brought them here,\u8232 although she\'92d entertained you royally\u8232 in her own home. Now you\'92re madly eager\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0740\u8232 to throw deadly fire on our sea-going ships,\u8232 to kill Achaean warriors. But you\'92ll be stopped,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[630]\u8232 no matter how much you now want to fight.\u8232 O Father Zeus, people say for wisdom\u8232 you exceed all others, men and gods alike.\u8232 Yet all this comes from you, the way you show\u8232 favours to these insolent men, these Trojans,\u8232 whose aggressive spirit has no limit,\u8232 who can never get enough of battle,\u8232 though they\'92re not winning in an equal fight.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0750\u8232 To all things there is a limit set\'97to sleep,\u8232 to love, sweet songs, and gorgeous dancing.\u8232 A man would rather have his fill of these, not war.\u8232 But Trojans here are gluttons for a fight.\'94\
