Thus the men keep fighting like a blazing fire.\uc0\u8232 But Hector, dear to Zeus, hadn\'92t heard and didn\'92t know\u8232 how the Achaeans were killing off his army\u8232 at the left end of the ships. Glory in this battle\u8232 would soon have been awarded to Achaeans\'97\u8232 that\'92s how powerfully Earthshaker Poseidon,\u8232 who enfolds the earth, was driving Argives forward,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0800\u8232 helping them with his own strength as well. But Hector\u8232 charged on from where he\'92d first breached the gates and wall,\u8232 smashing up the close-packed ranks of the Danaans,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[680]\u8232 right to the ships of Protesilaus and Ajax,\u8232 drawn up on the beach beside the blue-grey sea.\u8232 By these ships the wall was lowest. So there the fight\u8232 with men and horses was particularly fierce.\u8232 There Boeotians fought, Ionians in long tunics,\u8232 Locrians, Phthians, and glittering Epeians.\u8232 But they had trouble standing up to Hector\'92s charge,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0810\u8232 as he attacked the ships. They couldn\'92t push him back,\u8232 away from them, as he came up, like an inferno,\u8232 not even the finest men of the Athenians,\u8232 with their leader Menestheus, son of Peteos,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[690]\u8232 alongside Pheidas, Stichius, and brave Bias,\u8232 with the Epeians led by Meges, son of Phyleus,\u8232 Amphion, Dracius, and the Phthians,\u8232 led by Medon and Podarces, both brave men.\u8232 Medon was a bastard son of noble O\'efleus\u8232 and Ajax\'92s brother. But he lived in Phylace,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0820\u8232 far from his native land, for he\'92d killed a man,\u8232 one related to Eriopis, his stepmother,\u8232 wife of O\'efleus. Podarcus was Iphicles\'92 son,\u8232 child of Phylaces. These men in their armour\u8232 were fighting at the head of those brave Phthians,\u8232 standing with Boeotians to defend the ships.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[700]\
Ajax, son of O\'efleus, would not move away\uc0\u8232 from Ajax, son of Telamon\'97he fought beside him.\u8232 Just as in a meadow a pair of wine-dark oxen\u8232 strain with the same heart to pull a jointed plough,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0830\u8232 beads of sweat running from the bottom of their horns,\u8232 with nothing but a well-polished yoke between them,\u8232 as they labour down the furrows, till the plough\u8232 slices through the edges of the field\'97that\'92s the way\u8232 the two Ajaxes stood together then, side by side.\u8232 Telamonian Ajax had many comrades with him,\u8232 courageous soldiers, who\'92d relieve him of his shield\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[710]\u8232 when his sweaty limbs grew tired. But the Locrians\u8232 had not come forward with brave O\'eflean Ajax\'97\u8232 they lacked courage for fighting in the killing zone,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0840\u8232 for they had no plumed bronze helmets, no round shields,\u8232 and no ash spears. They\'92d come to Troy with Ajax\u8232 trusting in their bows and slings of twisted sheep\'92s wool.\u8232 Later they battled on with these, firing thick volleys,\u8232 breaking ranks of Trojans. So one group of men,\u8232 those with glittering weapons, fought at the front\u8232 against bronze-armed Hector and his Trojans,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[720]\u8232 while another shot from safe positions at the back.\u8232 The arrows drained the Trojans\'92 fighting spirit.\
